            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="paragraph">
                <h3>Experiment Process</h3>
                <p>There were 20 primary school children between the ages of 7 and 12 particapated in our experiment, and we recored the pressure data, took videos of sitting position in side view and the experiment itself.</p>
        </div>
        <img src="/images/icushion/Group 11.1.png" class="img-full-width">
        <div class="paragraph">
            <h3>Sitting Posture Analysis</h3>
            <p>We preliminarily analyzed the corresponding relationship between the inclination degree, the curvature degree and the hip pressure data, and completed <b>an analysis report</b>.</p>
            <p>Inclination degree = arctan∠3 <br/>
                Inclination degree = curvature（π-∠1-∠2）</p>
            <div class="image-middle-container">
                <img src="/images/icushion/Group 11.2.png" witdh="80%">
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="paragraph">
            <h3>Conclusion</h3>
            <p>Through the quantitative analysis of sitting postures and pressure figures, we came to three conclusions:<br/>
                1. When children are in reading, writing or painting, the pressure data is not very different. This shows that <b>learning scenarios do not need to be further divided</b>. <br/>
                2. Compared with sitting position, the relative position of children has a greater impact than sitting postures on pressure data. The <b>shape of the cushion should be able to fix the relative position of children sitting on it</b>.<br/>
                3. It is difficult to determine the degree of curvature of the back of a child only through the pressure data sampling of the cushion plane, so the <b>sample points should also be set on the backrest</b>.</p>
        </div>
